  <h1>Beneficiary Letter — New Zealand</h1>
  <p><strong>Prepared for:</strong> [Borrower Name] | <strong>Date:</strong> [Date]</p>

  <h2>What is an EPM?</h2>
  <p>The Equity Preservation Mortgage (EPM) is a secured loan where loan proceeds are invested. Investment returns pay mortgage interest and provide you monthly income.</p>

  <h2>What Your Beneficiaries Inherit</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The Property:</strong> Your home, registered at Land Registry, subject to the mortgage</li>
    <li><strong>Estate Value:</strong> Property value MINUS mortgage balance</li>
    <li><strong>NNEG Protection:</strong> Protects beneficiaries from inheriting debt exceeding property value</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Settlement Process</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Lender notified of your passing</li>
    <li>Estate administrator contacts Lender with death certificate and will/Letters of Administration</li>
    <li>Mortgage balance confirmed</li>
    <li>Options: (a) Sell property via settlement agent, pay Lender, remainder to estate; OR (b) Refinance/assume</li>
    <li>If property < mortgage debt, NNEG insurance covers shortfall. No debt recovery from estate.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Important Notes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>No Inheritance Tax:</strong> New Zealand has no estate or inheritance tax. Beneficiaries inherit property proceeds without tax liability.</li>
    <li><strong>Relationship Property:</strong> If property was acquired during a relationship, it may be relationship property subject to division. Check Family Court orders.</li>
    <li><strong>GST:</strong> Sale of property by estate may trigger GST in rare cases; consult with estate accountant.</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Estate representatives should seek independent legal advice from a NZ lawyer regarding estate settlement, relationship property, and title transfer.</strong></p>
</div>

